<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26270a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26270a">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26270a"> 270(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bifons</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[State religion]</font>&mdash;Thus, the simple reflection that the door is used for the double purpose of entrance and exit leads to the notion of the Janus of the State as <i><mark>bifons</mark></i> (&ldquo;two-faced&rdquo;): the thought of the door as the first part of the house to which one comes, produces the more abstract idea of Janus as the &ldquo;god of beginnings&rdquo;, in which character he has special charge of the first beginnings of human life (<i>Consevius</i>), the first hour of the day, the Calends of the month and the first month of the year in the later calendar: for the same reason his name takes the first place in the <i>indigitamenta</i> <font color="green">[list of gods invoked]</font>. <small> &ldquo;ROMAN RELIGION&rdquo; <a name="EBRR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRR"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 578</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
